R-Probability-Distributions

All of the common distributions are available in R, and for every distribution R can calculate various properties. There is a root name for each distribution (e.g norm for the normal distribution) and the following prefixes to the name of the distribution to do the following:

d to generate the probability mass or density function
Example: dnorm(x,mean,sd)

p to generate the probability \(P(X \le x)\) (the cdf)
Example: pnorm(q,mean,sd)

q to generate the quantile \(P(X \le x) > q\) (inverse cdf)
Example: qnorm(p,mean,sd)

r to generate a random variable having the specified distribution
Example: rnorm(n,mean,sd)

Distributions in R with their function names and function requirements (generally values of distribution parameters)

Distribution Functions Specifications
beta dbeta pbeta qbeta rbeta shape parameters \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\)
binomial dbinom pbinom qbinom rbinom number of trials and probability of success on each trial
cauchy dcauchy pcauchy qcauchy rcauchy location \(\alpha\) and scale \(\beta\) parameters
chi-square dchisq pchisq qchisq rchisq degrees of freedom
exponential dexp pexp qexp rexp rate \(\lambda\)
F df pf qf rf numerator and denominator degrees of freedom
gamma dgamma pgamma qgamma rgamma shape \(\alpha\) and scale \(\beta\) parameters
geometric dgeom pgeom qgeom rgeom probability of success
hypergeometric dhyper phyper qhyper rhyper number in group 1 (\(n\)), number in group 2 (\(m\)), number drawn (\(k\))
logistic dlogis plogis qlogis rlogis location and scale parameters
lognormal dlnorm plnorm qlnorm rlnorm mean \(\mu\) and standard deviation \(\sigma\) on the log scale
negative binomial dnbinom pnbinom qnbinom rnbinom number of trials and probability of success on each trial
normal dnorm pnorm qnorm rnorm mean \(\mu\) and standard deviation \(\sigma\)
poisson dpois ppois qpois rpois rate parameter \(\lambda\)
t dt pt qt rt degrees of freedom
uniform dunif punif qunif runif min and max (\(\theta_1\) and \(\theta_2\)) of the distribution
weibull dweibull pweibull qweibull rweibull shape \(\alpha\) and scale \(\beta\) parameters

Using d functions

The d functions find the pmf for discrete distributions and the pdf for continuous distributions, namely returning the probability density for a given value of random variable X, \(P(X=x)\). For a given range of values \(x_1,...,x_n\), we can find the density and plot the density function. For example, to generate the standard normal pdf, define some observations x, and apply dnorm with \(\mu=0\) and \(\sigma=1\) (note these are the default values of dnorm):

x <- seq(-3,3,0.01)
# Plot Normal Distribution
plot(x=x, y=dnorm(x, mean=0, sd=1), type='l')

Let’s look at the t distribution with different degrees of freedom and compare it to the standard normal distribution

# provide same x observations as above
x <- seq(-3,3,0.01)
# try different degrees of freedom
df <- c(1, 3, 5, 50)
# set up colours and labels for the functions and plot legend
colors <- c("red", "blue", "darkgreen", "gold", "black")
labels <- c("df=1", "df=3", "df=5", "df=50", "standard normal")
# plot Z first
plot(x, dnorm(x), type="l", lty=2, xlab="x value",
     ylab="Density", main="Comparison of t Distributions")
# add lines representing t-distribution
for (i in 1:4){
  lines(x, dt(x,df[i]), lwd=2, col=colors[i])
}
# add legend
legend("topright", title="t-Distribution",
       labels, lwd=2, lty=c(1, 1, 1, 1, 2), col=colors)

We see how when df->\(\infty\), t converges to the standard normal distribution.

For a binomial random variable, suppose you take a multiple choice exam with 10 questions. Each question has 5 possible answers, with only one being correct. You didn’t study so guess the answers. What is the probability of getting exactly 6 correct Pr(X=6)?

dbinom(6,size=10,prob=1/5)
[1] 0.005505024

The distribution of all possible results on the test

y<-dbinom(0:10,size=10,prob=1/5)
barplot(y,space=0,names.arg=c(0:10))

Using p functions

The p functions find \(F(x) = P(X \le x)\), thus providing the probability for the “lower tail” of the distribution. Basically, this function will return the probability for which a given number or a vector of numbers is less than or equal to a value. Should we wish to find the probability for the “upper tail”, we can choose the option lower=FALSE in any of the distribution functions. For example, an application of the Poisson distribution:
Suppose there are on average 10 asthmatic patients that come to a particular health clinic on a given day. What is the probability that only 4 will come to the clinic today?

ppois(4,lambda=10)
[1] 0.02925269

This is the probability that 4 or fewer will come to the clinic today. The probability of 5 or more coming to the clinic will be

ppois(4,lambda=10, lower=FALSE)
[1] 0.9707473

An example using the normal distribution, suppose we have data between -2 and 2 and we wish to find the probabilities of their values given that they come from a normal population with mean -1 and standard deviation 1. We plot the probabilities against each value of our random variable X.

x <- seq(-2,2,by=0.1)
y <- pnorm(x,mean=-1,sd=1)
plot(x,y, ylab="P(X<=x)",xlab="x")

Using q functions

The q functions are the inverse of the p functions, meaning that for a given probability the quantile (percentile) value q for the cumulative distribution will be returned \(P(X \le x) > q\). For instance, for a standard normal distribution the qnorm function for p=0.95 will return the z-score 1.64.

qnorm(0.95,mean=0,sd=1)
[1] 1.644854

Another example: find the 99th percentile of the \(\chi^2\) distribution with 6 degrees of freedom.

qchisq(0.99,6)
[1] 16.81189

Using r functions

The r functions generate a random sample of a specified size from the distribution of choice.
Let’s generate 7 observations from a uniform distribution on the interval [1,5] and sort it in ascending order

x<-runif(7,1,5)
sort(x)
[1] 1.292336 1.903070 2.845815 3.267600 4.196206 4.705819 4.725922

Additional uses of the functions

Suppose we know IQ scores are normally distributed with a mean of 100 and a standard deviation of 15. What proportion of children are expected to have an IQ between 80 and 120? This is an application of pnorm, and if we wish to plot the area under the normal distribution that corresponds to this area, we additionally apply dnorm.

# set up necessary parameters
mean=100
sd=15
lb=80
ub=120
# create vector of x's: 100 observations around the given mean and sd
x <- seq(-4,4,length=100)*sd + mean
# find probabilities for these values given the distribution parameters
hx <- dnorm(x,mean,sd)
# plot
plot(x, hx, type="n", xlab="IQ Values", ylab="", main="Normal Distribution", axes=FALSE)
# add lines at the upper and lower bounds
i <- x >= lb & x <= ub
lines(x, hx)
# create polygon for shading area of distribution
polygon(c(lb,x[i],ub), c(0,hx[i],0), col="lightblue") 
area <- pnorm(ub, mean, sd) - pnorm(lb, mean, sd)
# add title and axis labels
mtext(paste("P(",lb,"< IQ <",ub,")=",signif(area, digits=3)),3)
axis(1, at=seq(40, 160, 20), pos=0)
